abstract: PHILADELPHIA, July 2. -- This city passed through another period or torture to-day, and to-night at least fifty-two persons lie dead as a result of the excessive heat and more than 300 others were prostrated. abstract: John D. Quincy, Assistant Corporation Counsel, assigned to the Board of Building Commissioners, died on Monday in Brooklyn after an illness of three months, in his fifty-seventh year. abstract: By winning yesterday's baseball game from Chicago, the New Yorks have a comfortable hold on second place, with which to start their second Western trip. abstract: CHICAGO, July 3 -- Two new telescopes are being constructed at the Yerkes Observatory. One is a two-foot horizontal reflecting glass of 165 feet focal length, and from it much is expected. Images of the heavenly bodies will be brought into physical laboratories, where delicate instruments, which are useless in the open dome, can be employed.

abstract: HUDSON, N.Y., July 3 -- Samuel Moffat, the oldest brother of David Moffat of Denver, Col., died in Goshen yesterday. In 1857 he established the Bank of Nebraska, said to be the second founded west of the Missouri River, making the journey there on horseback and carrying $50,000 in gold. In 1874 he established the State Bank at Chatham, N.Y., and retired from active business in 1878.

abstract: Yesterday for Wall Street was quite unlike recent holidays: It was an actual vacation. Not only were all the Exchanges of the country closed, but no effort whatever was made to trade in the foreign markets. After the enervating heat of the early part of the week the brokers were only too glad to escape from the petty cares of business and to sacrifice their profits, in commissions and otherwise, for a rest.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, July 7. -- The North American to-morrow will publish a story to the effect that the entire coal transportation east of the Mississippi River will be divided among the railroads controlled by the Pennsylvania Railroad and the Vanderbilt and the Morgan interests. The Pennsylvania and Vanderbilt lines will carry all the coal produced in the bituminous regions, while the Morgan roads will control the entire anthracite transportation.

abstract: SEABRIGHT, N.J., July 10 -- Squadron A won the second match to-day on the Rumson Club's polo field near Seabright, and became possessors of the cup given by Theodore L. Myers for the best two out of three competitions. The squadron quartet beat the home team by 4 goals to 2 1/4. The game was played without handicap, but Rumson lost three-fourths of its 3 earned goals for safety penalties.

abstract: WICHITA, Kan., July 15 -- After a drought of four weeks, that has nearly caused the ruin of the entire crop, it rained here to-day. It was a curious crowd that stood in Main Street this morning, eagerly watching a dark cloud that was gradually obscuring the blue sky. At noon, however, the sky was again clear and hopes of rain were blasted.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, July 16 -- Railway and steel stocks were sagging in the local market to-day, but the strictly local list showed a better tone, notably the street railway shares. Philadelphia Traction was stronger, and the best gain was made by Electric and People's of America, which touched 96, against 94 3/4 yesterday.

abstract: BAR HARBOR, Me., July 16 -- The heat at Bar Harbor to-day was probably the highest ever known here. At midday the thermometer showed 96 degrees. Society kept indoors all morning, the links at Kebo were deserted, and not a yacht moved across the waters of the bay. This weather has been a revelation to Bar Harbor people, who never believed that such a condition could exist.

abstract: HAMPTON, Va., July 18 -- At its second day's session here the Hampton Negro Conference devoted a large share of the morning to a discussion of disfranchisement and education. abstract: BALTIMORE, July 18 -- The market today made a slight improvement in the matter of activity, with an upward tendency in price. abstract: WASHINGTON, July 18 -- A preliminary statement of the Chinese population, derived from the returns of the twelfth census, was issued by Director Merriam today. It shows that there are approximately 89,800 Chinese in the United States proper, as against 107,475 in 1890. abstract: LONDON, July 19. -- The Duke of Marlborough is about to appear in a new role. There will be held at Blenheim Palace, on Aug. 10, one of the largest political demonstrations of recent times. Three thousand delegates from Conservative and Liberal Unionist associations throughout the country will be present, and the gathering will number in all about 7,000.

abstract: To The New York Times Saturday Review. As a work of literature, to be read in the closet, Shakespeare's plays commend themselves for their complete mastery of human life as no other work does. They are literature, though, of the Homeric school, not of the Virgilian. They lack the learning of the schools, make errors no scholar would make, use English no scholar would use, and look on life through no learned spectacles.

abstract: IT was three years ago. I was in Paris. Half student and hall tourist. I was in search of any intellectual amusement. abstract: BOSTON, July 22. -- The eleventh, annual tennis tournament for the Longwood Trophy, held by Whitman, began at Longwood to-day with forty-two entries, including Wright, Davis, Ward, Larned, and Hobart. All of these, except Davis, who was defending his Magnolia title, were seen to-day. Wright had an easy double win, though Pier pushed him for one set, Wright showed good form and seemed to have recovered from a temporary fit of ill condition.

abstract: PITTSBURG, July 22. -- Neither of the looked-for strike programmes for Wellsville or McKeesport were carried out today. At Wellsville the importation of men failed to materialize, and at McKeesport the attempt to resume at the Dewees Wood tube plant was not made. At both points, which are considered by each side to be the strik centres, the situation is in statu quo, neither of the parties to the controversy having made any decided move.

abstract: VINEYARD HAVEN, Mass., July 26. -- The squadron run of the New York Yacht Club to-day from Newport to Martha's Vineyard proved to be the first fizzle of the cruise. abstract: ABOUT twenty-five young women, Summer boarders here, marched into Mr. Silas Larrabee's front yard last night and took possession of it.
